# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: styx-rule
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:styx-rule/boranes] A **borane** is a compound with the formula B*x*H*y*R*z* although examples include multi-boron derivatives.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Most of the known group 13 hydrides belong to this class.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] A large family of boron hydride clusters is also known.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] In addition to some applications in organic chemistry, the boranes have attracted much attention as they exhibit structures and bonding that differs strongly from the patterns seen in hydrocarbons.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Hybrids of boranes and hydrocarbons, the carboranes, are also a well developed class of compounds.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] The development of the chemistry of boranes led to innovations in synthetic methods as well as structure and bonding.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] First, new synthetic techniques were required to handle diborane and many of its derivatives, which are both pyrophoric and volatile.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Alfred Stock invented the glass vacuum line for this purpose.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] The structure of diborane was correctly predicted in 1943 many years after its discovery.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Interest in boranes increased during World War II due to the potential of uranium borohydride for enrichment of the uranium isotopes and as a source of hydrogen for inflating weather balloons.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] In the US, a team led by Schlesinger developed the basic chemistry of the anionic boron hydrides and the related aluminium hydrides.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Schlesinger's work laid the foundation for a host of boron hydride reagents for organic synthesis, most of which were developed by his student Herbert C.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Borane-based reagents are now widely used in organic synthesis.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Brown was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1979 for this work.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Most boranes are prepared directly or indirectly from diborane.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Alkyl and aryl boranes can also be produced by alkylation of chloroboranes and boronic esters.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] The parent boranes are binary boron hydrides, starting with borane (BH3) and its dimer diborane (B2H6).
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Pyrolysis of these species leads to higher boranes, such as tetraborane (B4H10) and pentaborane (B5H9).
[src:styx-rule/boranes] These two are early members of the boron hydride clusters.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] This family of boron hydrides includes mono- and dialkylboranes.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] With bulky substituents, primary and secondary boranes are more readily isolable and even useful.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Examples include thexylborane and 9-BBN.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Almost all primary and secondary boranes are dimeric with bridging hydrides.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Most work focuses on trialkyl and triaryl boranes.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] These are all monomers (in contrast to the corresponding trialkyl and triarylaluminium compounds).
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Well known examples are trimethylboron, triethylboron, and triphenylboron.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Many tertiary boranes are produced by hydroboration.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] The lowest borane, BH3 exists only transiently, dimerizing instantly to form diborane, B2H6.
[src:styx-rule/boranes] Its adduct borane–tetrahydrofuran and borane–dimethylsulfide are useful in hydroboration reactions.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is synthesized entirely by cosmic ray spallation and supernovas and not by stellar nucleosynthesis, so it is a low-abundance element in the Solar System and in the Earth's crust.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It constitutes about 0.001 percent by weight of Earth's crust.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is concentrated on Earth by the water-solubility of its more common naturally occurring compounds, the borate minerals.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These are mined industrially as evaporites, such as borax and kernite.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The largest known deposits are in Turkey, the largest producer of boron minerals.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Elemental boron is found in small amounts in meteoroids, but chemically uncombined boron is not otherwise found naturally on Earth.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Several allotropes exist: amorphous boron is a brown powder; crystalline boron is silvery to black, extremely hard (9.3 on the Mohs scale), and a poor electrical conductor at room temperature (1.5 × 10−6 Ω−1 cm−1 room temperature electrical conductivity).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The primary use of the element itself is as boron filaments with applications similar to carbon fibers in some high-strength materials.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is primarily used in chemical compounds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] About half of all production consumed globally is an additive in fiberglass for insulation and structural materials.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The next leading use is in polymers and ceramics in high-strength, lightweight structural and heat-resistant materials.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borosilicate glass is desired for its greater strength and thermal shock resistance than ordinary soda lime glass.
[src:styx-rule/boron] As sodium perborate, it is used as a bleach.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A small amount is used as a dopant in semiconductors and reagent intermediates in the synthesis of organic fine chemicals.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A few boron-containing organic pharmaceuticals are used or are in study.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Natural boron is composed of two stable isotopes, one of which (boron-10) has a number of uses as a neutron-capturing agent.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borates have low toxicity in mammals (similar to table salt) but are more toxic to arthropods and are occasionally used as insecticides.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron-containing organic antibiotics are known.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Although only traces are required, boron is an essential plant nutrient.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The word *boron* was coined from *borax*, the mineral from which it was isolated, by analogy with *carbon*, which boron resembles chemically.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borax in its mineral form (then known as tincal) first saw use as a glaze, beginning in China circa 300 AD.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some crude borax traveled westward, and was apparently mentioned by the alchemist Jabir ibn Hayyan around 700 AD.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Marco Polo brought some glazes back to Italy in the 13th century.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Georgius Agricola, in around 1600, reported the use of borax as a flux in metallurgy.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In 1777, boric acid was recognized in the hot springs (soffioni) near Florence, Italy, at which point it became known as *sal sedativum*, with ostensible medical benefits.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The mineral was named sassolite after Sasso Pisano in Italy.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Sasso was the main source of European borax from 1827 to 1872, when American sources replaced it.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron compounds were rarely used until the late 1800s when Francis Marion Smith's Pacific Coast Borax Company first popularized and produced them in volume at low cost.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron was not recognized as an element until it was isolated by Sir Humphry Davy and by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac and Louis Jacques Thénard.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In 1808, Davy observed that electric current sent through a solution of borates produced a brown precipitate on one of the electrodes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In his subsequent experiments, he used potassium to reduce boric acid instead of electrolysis.
[src:styx-rule/boron] He produced enough boron to confirm a new element and named it *boracium*.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Gay-Lussac and Thénard used iron to reduce boric acid at high temperatures.
[src:styx-rule/boron] By oxidizing boron with air, they showed that boric acid is its oxidation product.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Jöns Jacob Berzelius identified it as an element in 1824.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Pure boron was arguably first produced by the American chemist Ezekiel Weintraub in 1909.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron has two naturally occurring and stable isotopes, 11B (80.1%) and 10B (19.9%).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The mass difference results in a wide range of δ11B values, which are defined as a fractional difference between the 11B and 10B and traditionally expressed in parts per thousand, in natural waters ranging from −16 to +59.
[src:styx-rule/boron] There are 13 known isotopes of boron; the shortest-lived isotope is 7B which decays through proton emission and alpha decay with a half-life of 3.5×10−22 s.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Isotopic fractionation of boron is controlled by the exchange reactions of the boron species B(OH)3 and [B(OH)4]−.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron isotopes are also fractionated during mineral crystallization, during H2O phase changes in hydrothermal systems, and during hydrothermal alteration of rock.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The latter effect results in preferential removal of the [10B(OH)4]− ion onto clays.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It results in solutions enriched in 11B(OH)3 and therefore may be responsible for the large 11B enrichment in seawater relative to both oceanic crust and continental crust; this difference may act as an isotopic signature.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The exotic 17B exhibits a nuclear halo, i.e. its radius is appreciably larger than that predicted by the liquid drop model.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The nuclear spin of 10B is 3 and that of 11B is ⁠3/2⁠.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These isotopes are therefore of use in nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, and spectrometers specially adapted to detecting the boron-11 nuclei are available commercially.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The 10B and 11B nuclei also cause splitting in the resonances of attached nuclei.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron forms four major allotropes: α-rhombohedral and β-rhombohedral (α-R and β-R), γ-orthorhombic (γ), and β-tetragonal (β-T).
[src:styx-rule/boron] All four phases are stable at ambient conditions. β-rhombohedral is the most stable and the most common.
[src:styx-rule/boron] An α-tetragonal phase also exists (α-T) but is very difficult to produce without significant contamination.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Most of the phases are based on B12 icosahedra, but the γ phase can be described as a rocksalt-type arrangement of the icosahedra and B2 atomic pairs.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It can be produced by compressing other boron phases to 12–20 GPa and heating to 1500–1800 °C; it remains stable after releasing the temperature and pressure.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The β-T phase is produced at similar pressures, but higher temperatures of 1800–2200 °C.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The α-T and β-T phases might coexist at ambient conditions, with the β-T phase being the more stable.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Compressing boron above 160 GPa produces a boron phase with an as yet unknown structure, and this phase is a superconductor at temperatures below 6–12 K.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Atomic boron is the lightest element having an electron in a p-orbital in its ground state.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Its first three ionization energies are higher than those for heavier group III elements, reflecting its electropositive character.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Elemental boron is rare and poorly studied because the pure material is extremely difficult to prepare.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Most studies of "boron" involve samples that contain small amounts of carbon.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Very pure boron is produced with difficulty because of contamination by carbon or other elements that resist removal.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some early routes to elemental boron involved the reduction of boric oxide with metals such as magnesium or aluminium.
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, the product was often contaminated with borides of those metals.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Pure boron can be prepared by reducing volatile boron halides with hydrogen at high temperatures.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Ultrapure boron for use in the semiconductor industry is produced by the decomposition of diborane at high temperatures and then further purified by the zone melting or Czochralski processes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Crystalline boron is a hard, black material with a melting point of above 2000 °C.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Crystalline boron is chemically inert and resistant to attack by boiling hydrofluoric or hydrochloric acid.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When finely divided, it is attacked slowly by hot concentrated hydrogen peroxide, hot concentrated nitric acid, hot sulfuric acid, or hot mixture of sulfuric and chromic acids.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Since elemental boron is very rare, its chemical reactions are of little significance.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The elemental form is not typically used as a precursor to compounds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Instead, boron compounds are produced from borates.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When exposed to air, under normal conditions, a protective oxide or hydroxide layer forms on the surface of boron, which prevents further corrosion.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The rate of oxidation of boron depends on the crystallinity, particle size, purity and temperature.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In some ways, boron is comparable to carbon in its capability to form stable covalently bonded molecular networks (even nominally disordered (amorphous) boron contains boron icosahedra, which are bonded randomly to each other without long-range order.).
[src:styx-rule/boron] In terms of chemical behavior, boron compounds resemble silicon due to their diagonal relationship.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Aluminium, the heavier congener of boron, does not behave analogously to boron: it is far more electropositive, it is larger, and it tends not to form homoatomic Al-Al bonds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In the most familiar compounds, boron has the formal oxidation state III.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These include the common oxides, sulfides, nitrides, and halides, as well as organic derivatives.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron compounds often violate the octet rule.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron forms the complete series of trihalides, i.e.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The trihalides adopt a planar trigonal structures, in contrast to the behavior of aluminium trihalides.
[src:styx-rule/boron] All charge-neutral boron halides violate the octet rule; hence, they are typically Lewis acidic.
[src:styx-rule/boron] For example, boron trifluoride (BF3) combines eagerly with fluoride sources to give the tetrafluoroborate anion, BF4−.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron trifluoride is used in the petrochemical industry as a catalyst.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The halides react with water to form boric acid.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Other boron halides include those with B-B bonding, such as B2F4 and B4Cl4.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Larger polyhedral boron(I) halides also exist, e.g.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron-containing minerals exclusively exist as oxides of B(III), often associated with other elements.
[src:styx-rule/boron] More than one hundred borate minerals are known.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These minerals resemble silicates in some respect, although it is often found not only in a tetrahedral coordination with oxygen, but also in a trigonal planar configuration.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The borates can be subdivided into two classes, anhydrous and the far more common hydrates.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The hydrates contain B-OH groups and sometimes water of crystallization.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A typical motif is exemplified by the tetraborate anions of the common mineral borax.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The formal negative charge of the tetrahedral borate center is balanced by sodium (Na+).
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some of the complexity of the borates is exemplified by the inventory of zinc borates, which are common wood preservatives and fire retardants: 4ZnO·B2O3·H2O, ZnO·B2O3·1.12H2O, ZnO·B2O3·2H2O, 6ZnO·5B2O3·3H2O, 2ZnO·3B2O3·7H2O, 2ZnO·3B2O3·3H2O, 3ZnO·5B2O3·14H2O, and ZnO·5B2O3·4.5H2O.
[src:styx-rule/boron] As illustrated by the preceding examples, borate anions tend to condense by formation of B-O-B bonds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borosilicates, with B-O-Si, and borophosphates, with B-O-P linkages, are also well represented in both minerals and synthetic compounds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Related to the oxides are the alkoxides and boronic acids with the formula B(OR)3 and R2BOH, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron forms a wide variety of such metal-organic compounds, some of which are used in the synthesis of pharmaceuticals.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These developments, especially the Suzuki reaction, was recognized with the 2010 Nobel Prize in Chemistry to Akira Suzuki.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boranes and borohydrides are compounds of boron and hydrogen that are neutral and anionic, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Sodium borohydride is the progenitor of the boranes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Diborane is the dimer of the parent called borane, BH3.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Having a formula akin to ethane's (C2H6), diborane adopts a very different structure, featuring a pair of bridging H atoms.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This unusual structure, which was deduced only in the 1940s, was an early indication of the complexity of boron chemistry.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Pyrolysis of diborane gives boron hydride clusters such as pentaborane(9) B5H9 and decaborane B10H14.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A large number of anionic boron hydrides are also known, e.g. [B3H8]− and [B12H12]2−.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In these cluster compounds, boron has a coordination number greater than four.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When at least one boron atom is replaced by another elements, heteroboranes are formed.
[src:styx-rule/boron] They have similar structures of their parent boranes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The analysis of the bonding in these polyhedra clusters earned William N.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Lipscomb the 1976 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "studies on the structure of boranes illuminating problems of chemical bonding".
[src:styx-rule/boron] Not only are their structures unusual, many of the boranes are extremely reactive.
[src:styx-rule/boron] For example, a widely used procedure for pentaborane states that it will "spontaneously inflame or explode in air".
[src:styx-rule/boron] A large number of organoboron compounds, species with B-C bonds, are known.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Many organoboron compounds are produced from hydroboration, the addition of B-H bonds to C=C and C≡C bonds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This regiochemistry, i.e. the tendency of B to attach to the terminal carbon - is explained by the polarization of the bonds in boranes, which is indicated as Bδ+-Hδ-.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Hydroboration opened the doors for many subsequent reactions, several of which are useful in the synthesis of complex organic compounds.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The significance of these methods was recognized by the award of Nobel Prize in Chemistry to H.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Even complicated boron hydrides, such as decaborane, undergo hydroboration.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Like the volatile boranes, the alkyl boranes ignite spontaneously in air.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In the 1950s, several studies examined the use of boranes as energy-increasing "Zip fuel" additives for jet fuel.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Triorganoboron(III) compounds are trigonal planar and exhibit weak Lewis acidity.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This behavior contrasts with that of triorganoaluminium compounds (see trimethylaluminium), which are tetrahedral with bridging alkyl groups.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A compound with the B≡C triple bond was synthesized for the first time in 2025.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The boron-nitrides follow the pattern of avoiding B-B and N-N bonds; only B-N bonding is observed generally.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The boron nitrides exhibit structures analogous to various allotropes of carbon, including graphite, diamond, and nanotubes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This similarity reflects the fact that B and N have eight valence electrons as does a pair of carbon atoms.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In cubic boron nitride (tradename Borazon), boron and nitrogen atoms are tetrahedral, just like carbon in diamond.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Cubic boron nitride, among other applications, is used as an abrasive, as its hardness is comparable with that of diamond.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN) is the BN analogue of graphite, consisting of sheets of alternating B and N atoms.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These sheets stack with boron and nitrogen in registry between the sheets.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Graphite and h-BN have very different properties, although both are lubricants, as these planes slip past each other easily.
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, h-BN is a relatively poor electrical and thermal conductor in the planar directions.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Molecular analogues of boron nitrides are represented by borazine, (BH)3(NH)3.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron carbide's structure is only approximately reflected in its formula of B4C, and it shows a clear depletion of carbon from this suggested stoichiometric ratio.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This is due to its very complex structure.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The substance can be seen with empirical formula B12C3 (i.e., with B12 dodecahedra being a motif), but with less carbon, as the suggested C3 units are replaced with C-B-C chains, and some smaller (B6) octahedra are present as well (see the boron carbide article for structural analysis).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The repeating polymer plus semi-crystalline structure of boron carbide gives it great structural strength per weight.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Binary metal-boron compounds, the metal borides, contain only boron and a metal.
[src:styx-rule/boron] They are metallic, very hard, with high melting points.
[src:styx-rule/boron] TiB2, ZrB2, and HfB2 have melting points above 3000 °C.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The borides can be classified loosely as boron rich or metal rich, for example the compound YB66 at one extreme through to Nd2Fe14B at the other.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The generally accepted definition is that if the ratio of boron atoms to metal atoms is 4:1 or more, the compound is boron rich; if it is less, then it is metal rich.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some metal borides find specialized applications as hard materials for cutting tools.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is rare in the universe and Solar System.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The amount of boron formed in the Big Bang was negligible.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is not generated in the normal course of stellar nucleosynthesis, and is destroyed in stellar interiors.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In the high oxygen environment of the Earth's surface, boron is always found fully oxidized to borate.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron does not appear on Earth in elemental form.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Extremely small traces of elemental boron were detected in Lunar regolith.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Although boron is a relatively rare element in the Earth's crust, representing only 0.001% of the crust mass, it can be highly concentrated by the action of water, in which many borates are soluble.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is found naturally combined in compounds such as borax and boric acid (sometimes found in volcanic spring waters).
[src:styx-rule/boron] Over a hundred borate minerals are known.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Economically important sources of boron are the minerals colemanite, rasorite (kernite), ulexite, and tincal.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Together, these constitute 90% of mined boron-containing ore.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The largest global borax deposits known, many still untapped, are in Central and Western Turkey, including the provinces of Eskişehir, Kütahya and Balıkesir.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Global proven boron mineral mining reserves exceed one billion metric tonnes, against a yearly production of about four million tonnes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Turkey and the United States are the largest producers of boron products.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Turkey produces about half of the global yearly demand through Eti Mine Works (Turkish: *Eti Maden İşletmeleri*), a Turkish state-owned mining and chemicals company focusing on boron products.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It holds a government monopoly on the mining of borate minerals in Turkey, which possesses 72% of the world's known deposits.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In 2012, it held a 47% share of production of global borate minerals, ahead of its main competitor, Rio Tinto Group.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Almost a quarter (23%) of global boron production comes from the Rio Tinto Borax Mine (also known as the U.S.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The average cost of crystalline elemental boron was US$5/g in 2008.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Elemental boron is chiefly used in making boron fibers, where it is deposited by chemical vapor deposition on a tungsten core (see below).
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron fibers are used in lightweight composite applications, such as high strength tapes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This use is a very small fraction of total boron use.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is introduced into semiconductors as boron compounds by ion implantation.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Estimated global consumption of boron (almost entirely as boron compounds) was about 4 million tonnes of B2O3 in 2012.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The cost of boron compounds such as borax and kernite was cumulatively US$377/tonne in 2019.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Increasing demand for boric acid has led a number of producers to invest in additional capacity.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Turkey's state-owned Eti Mine Works opened a new boric acid plant with the production capacity of 100,000 tonnes per year at Emet in 2003.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Rio Tinto Group increased the capacity of its boron plant from 260,000 tonnes per year in 2003 to 310,000 tonnes per year by May 2005, with plans to grow this to 366,000 tonnes per year in 2006.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The rise in global demand has been driven by high growth rates in glass fiber, fiberglass, and borosilicate glassware production.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A rapid increase in the manufacture of reinforcement-grade boron-containing fiberglass in Asia has offset the development of boron-free reinforcement-grade fiberglass in Europe and the US.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The recent rises in energy prices may lead to greater use of insulation-grade fiberglass, with consequent growth in the boron consumption.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Roskill Consulting Group forecasts that world demand for boron will grow by 3.4% per year to reach 21 million tonnes by 2010.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The highest growth in demand is expected to be in Asia where demand could rise by an average 5.7% per year.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Nearly all boron ore extracted from the Earth is refined as boric acid and sodium tetraborate pentahydrate.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In the United States, 70% of the boron is used for the production of glass and ceramics.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The major global industrial-scale use of boron compounds (about 46% of end-use) is in production of glass fiber for boron-containing insulating and structural fiberglasses, especially in Asia.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is added to the glass as borax pentahydrate or boron oxide to influence the strength or fluxing qualities of the glass fibers.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Another 10% of global boron production is for borosilicate glass as used in high strength glassware.
[src:styx-rule/boron] About 15% of global boron is used in boron ceramics, including super-hard materials discussed below.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Agriculture consumes 11% of global boron production.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Bleaches and detergents consume about 6%.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Fiberglasses, a fiber reinforced polymer, sometimes contains borosilicate, borax, or boron oxide that is added to increase the strength of the glass.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The highly boronated glasses, E-glass (named for "Electrical" use), are alumino-borosilicate glass.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Another common high-boron glass, C-glass, also has a high boron oxide content and is used for glass staple fibers and insulation.
[src:styx-rule/boron] D-glass is a borosilicate glass named for its low dielectric constant.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Because of the ubiquitous use of fiberglass in construction and insulation, boron-containing fiberglasses consume over half the global production of boron and are the single largest commercial boron market.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borosilicate glass, which is typically 12–15% B2O3, 80% SiO2, and 2% Al2O3, has a low coefficient of thermal expansion, giving it a good resistance to thermal shock.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Schott AG's "Duran" and Owens-Corning's trademarked Pyrex are two major brand names for this glass, used both in laboratory glassware and in consumer cookware and bakeware, chiefly for this reason.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron fibers (boron filaments) are high-strength, lightweight materials that are used chiefly for advanced aerospace structures as a component of composite materials, as well as limited production consumer and sporting goods such as golf clubs and fishing rods.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The fibers can be produced by chemical vapor deposition of boron on a tungsten filament.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron fibers and sub-millimeter sized crystalline boron springs are produced by laser-assisted chemical vapor deposition.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Translation of the focused laser beam allows production of complex helical structures.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Such structures show good mechanical properties (elastic modulus 450 GPa, fracture strain 3.7%, fracture stress 17 GPa) and can be applied as reinforcement of ceramics or in micromechanical systems.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron carbide's ability to absorb neutrons without forming long-lived radionuclides (especially when doped with extra boron-10) makes the material attractive as an absorbent for neutron radiation arising in nuclear power plants.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Nuclear applications of boron carbide include shielding, control rods, and shut-down pellets.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Within control rods, boron carbide is often powdered to increase its surface area.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron carbide and cubic boron nitride powders are widely used as abrasives.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron nitride is a material isoelectronic to carbon.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Similar to carbon, it has both hexagonal (soft graphite-like h-BN) and cubic (hard, diamond-like c-BN) forms. h-BN is used as a high temperature component and lubricant. c-BN, also known under commercial name borazon, is a superior abrasive.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Its hardness is only slightly less than that of diamond, while its chemical stability is greater.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Heterodiamond (also called BCN) is another diamond-like boron compound.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is added to boron steels at the level of a few parts per million to increase hardenability.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Higher percentages are added to steels used in the nuclear industry due to boron's neutron absorption ability.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron can also increase the surface hardness of steels and alloys through boriding.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Additionally metal borides are used for coating tools through chemical vapor deposition or physical vapor deposition.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Implantation of boron ions into metals and alloys, through ion implantation or ion beam deposition, results in a spectacular increase in surface resistance and microhardness.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Laser alloying has also been used successfully for the same purpose.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These borides are an alternative to diamond coated tools, and their surfaces have similar properties to those of the bulk boride.
[src:styx-rule/boron] For example, rhenium diboride can be produced at ambient pressures but is rather expensive because of the cost of rhenium.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The hardness of ReB2 exhibits considerable anisotropy because of its hexagonal layered structure.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Its value is comparable to that of tungsten carbide, silicon carbide, titanium diboride, or zirconium diboride.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Similarly, AlMgB14 + TiB2 composites possess high hardness and wear resistance and are used in either bulk form or as coatings for components exposed to high temperatures and wear loads.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Borax is used in various household laundry and cleaning products.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is also present in some tooth bleaching formulas.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Sodium perborate serves as a source of active oxygen in many detergents, laundry detergents, cleaning products, and laundry bleaches.
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, despite its name, "Borateem" laundry bleach no longer contains any boron compounds, using sodium percarbonate instead as a bleaching agent.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Zinc borates and boric acid, popularized as fire retardants, are widely used as wood preservatives and insecticides.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boric acid is also used as a domestic insecticide.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is a useful dopant for such semiconductors as silicon, germanium, and silicon carbide.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Having one fewer valence electron than the host atom, it donates a hole, resulting in p-type conductivity.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The traditional method of doping semiconductors with boron is via atomic diffusion at high temperatures.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This process uses either solid (B2O3), liquid (BBr3), or gaseous boron sources (B2H6 or BF3).
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, after the 1970s, it was mostly replaced by ion implantation, which relies mostly on BF3 as a boron source.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron trichloride gas is also an important chemical in the semiconductor industry for the plasma etching of metals and their oxides.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Triethylborane is also injected into vapor deposition reactors as a boron source.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Examples are the plasma deposition of boron-containing hard carbon films, silicon nitride–boron nitride films, and the doping of diamond film with boron.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is a component of neodymium magnets (Nd2Fe14B), which are among the strongest type of permanent magnet.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These magnets are found in a variety of electromechanical and electronic devices such as in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) medical imaging systems and in compact and relatively small motors and actuators.
[src:styx-rule/boron] As examples, computer hard disk drive, CD, and DVD players rely on neodymium magnet motors to deliver intense rotary power in a compact package.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In mobile phones, "Neo" magnets provide the magnetic field which allows tiny speakers to deliver appreciable audio power.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron shielding is used as a control for nuclear reactors, taking advantage of its high cross-section for neutron capture.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In pressurized water reactors, a variable concentration of boronic acid in the cooling water is used as a neutron poison to compensate the variable reactivity of the fuel.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When new rods are inserted, the concentration of boronic acid is maximal.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron plays a role in pharmaceutical and biological applications as it is found in various antibiotics produced by bacteria, such as boromycins, aplasmomycins, borophycins, and tartrolons.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These antibiotics have shown inhibitory effects on the growth of certain bacteria, fungi, and protozoa.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is also being studied for its potential medicinal applications, including its incorporation into biologically active molecules for therapies like boron neutron capture therapy for brain tumors.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some boron-containing biomolecules may act as signaling molecules interacting with cell surfaces, suggesting a role in cellular communication.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boric acid and its salts, known as borates, are widely used in cleaners and fertilizers.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boric acid is a major component of some skin treatments; however, dermal exposure to high concentrations of boron can lead to severe adverse health effects including death, particularly when the skin is damaged.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Consumption of boric acid can also lead to abdominal pain, vomiting, and diarrhea.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The chemical is absorbed by the gastrointestinal system.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Mild solutions of boric acid have been used as eye antiseptics.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron appears as an active element in the organic pharmaceutical bortezomib, a class of drug called the proteasome inhibitor, for treating myeloma and one form of lymphoma.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The boron atom in bortezomib binds the catalytic site of the 26S proteasome.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Tavaborole is an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase inhibitor which is used to treat toenail fungus.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Dioxaborolane chemistry enables radioactive fluoride (18F) labeling of antibodies or red blood cells, which allows for positron emission tomography (PET) imaging of cancer and hemorrhages, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The dual-modality small molecule targeting PSMA was tested in humans and found the location of primary and metastatic prostate cancer, aided the fluorescence-guided removal of cancer, and detected single cancer cells in tissue margins.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Magnesium diboride (MgB2) is a superconductor with a transition temperature of 39 K.
[src:styx-rule/boron] MgB2 wires are produced with the powder-in-tube process and applied in superconducting magnets.
[src:styx-rule/boron] A project at CERN to make MgB2 cables has resulted in superconducting test cables able to carry 20,000 amperes for extremely high current distribution applications, such as the contemplated high luminosity version of the Large Hadron Collider.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Because of its high neutron cross-section, boron-10 is often used to control fission in nuclear reactors as a neutron-capturing substance.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Several industrial-scale enrichment processes have been developed; however, only the fractionated vacuum distillation of the dimethyl ether adduct of boron trifluoride (DME-BF3) and column chromatography of borates are being used.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Cosmic radiation produces secondary neutrons when it hits spacecraft structures.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Those neutrons are captured in 10B if it is present in the spacecraft's semiconductors, producing a gamma ray, an alpha particle, and a lithium ion.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Those resultant decay products may then irradiate nearby semiconductor "chip" structures, causing data loss (bit flipping, or single event upset).
[src:styx-rule/boron] In radiation-hardened semiconductor designs, one countermeasure is to use *depleted boron*, which is greatly enriched in 11B and contains almost no 10B.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This is useful because 11B is largely immune to radiation damage.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Depleted boron is a byproduct of the nuclear industry (see above).
[src:styx-rule/boron] 11B is also a candidate as a fuel for aneutronic fusion.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When struck by a proton with energy of about 500 keV, it produces three alpha particles and 8.7 MeV of energy.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Most other fusion reactions involving hydrogen and helium produce penetrating neutron radiation, which weakens reactor structures and induces long-term radioactivity, thereby endangering operating personnel.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The alpha particles from 11B fusion can be turned directly into electric power, and all radiation stops as soon as the reactor is turned off.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The 10B isotope is useful for capturing thermal neutrons (see neutron cross section).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The nuclear industry enriches natural boron to nearly pure 10B.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The less valuable by-product, depleted boron, is nearly pure 11B.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Enriched boron or 10B is both used in radiation shielding and is the primary nuclide used in neutron capture therapy of cancer.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In the latter ("boron neutron capture therapy" or BNCT), a compound containing 10B is incorporated into a pharmaceutical which is selectively taken up by a malignant tumor and tissues near it.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The patient is then treated with a beam of low energy neutrons at a relatively low neutron radiation dose.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The neutrons trigger energetic and short-range secondary alpha particle and lithium-7 heavy ion radiation that are products of the boron-neutron nuclear reaction, and this ion radiation additionally bombards the tumor, especially from inside the tumor cells.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In nuclear reactors, 10B is used for reactivity control and in emergency shutdown systems.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It can serve either function in the form of borosilicate control rods or as boric acid.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In pressurized water reactors, 10B boric acid is added to the reactor coolant after the plant is shut down for refueling.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When the plant is started up again, the boric acid is slowly filtered out over many months as fissile material is used up and the fuel becomes less reactive.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron has been investigated for possible applications in nuclear fusion research.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is commonly used for conditioning the walls in fusion reactors by depositing boron coatings on plasma-facing components and walls to reduce the release of hydrogen and impurities from the surfaces.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is also being used for the dissipation of energy in the fusion plasma boundary to suppress excessive energy bursts and heat fluxes to the walls.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In neutron capture therapy (NCT) for malignant brain tumors, boron is researched to be used for selectively targeting and destroying tumor cells.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The goal is to deliver higher concentrations of the non-radioactive boron isotope (10B) to the tumor cells than to the surrounding normal tissues.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When these 10B-containing cells are irradiated with low-energy thermal neutrons, they undergo nuclear capture reactions, releasing high linear energy transfer (LET) particles such as alpha particles and lithium-7 nuclei within a limited path length.
[src:styx-rule/boron] These high-LET particles can destroy the adjacent tumor cells without causing significant harm to nearby normal cells.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron acts as a selective agent due to its ability to absorb thermal neutrons and produce short-range physical effects primarily affecting the targeted tissue region.
[src:styx-rule/boron] This binary approach allows for precise tumor cell killing while sparing healthy tissues.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The effective delivery of boron involves administering boron compounds or carriers capable of accumulating selectively in tumor cells compared to surrounding tissue.
[src:styx-rule/boron] BSH and BPA have been used clinically, but research continues to identify more optimal carriers.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Accelerator-based neutron sources have also been developed recently as an alternative to reactor-based sources, leading to improved efficiency and enhanced clinical outcomes in NCT.
[src:styx-rule/boron] By employing the properties of boron isotopes and targeted irradiation techniques, NCT offers a potential approach to treating malignant brain tumors by selectively killing cancer cells while minimizing the damage caused by traditional radiation therapies.
[src:styx-rule/boron] BNCT has shown promising results in clinical trials for various other malignancies, including glioblastoma, head and neck cancer, cutaneous melanoma, hepatocellular carcinoma, lung cancer, and extramammary Paget's disease.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The treatment involves a nuclear reaction between nonradioactive boron-10 isotope and low-energy thermal or high-energy epithermal neutrons to generate α particles and lithium nuclei that selectively destroy DNA in tumor cells.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The primary challenge lies in developing efficient boron agents with higher content and specific targeting properties tailored for NCT.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Integration of tumor-targeting strategies with NCT could potentially establish it as a practical personalized treatment option for different types of cancers.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Ongoing research explores new boron compounds, optimization strategies, theranostic agents, and radiobiological advances to overcome limitations and cost-effectively improve patient outcomes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is an essential plant nutrient, required primarily for maintaining the integrity of cell walls.
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, high soil concentrations of greater than 1.0 ppm lead to marginal and tip necrosis in leaves as well as poor overall growth performance.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Levels as low as 0.8 ppm produce these same symptoms in plants that are particularly sensitive to boron in the soil.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Nearly all plants, even those somewhat tolerant of soil boron, will show at least some symptoms of boron toxicity when soil boron content is greater than 1.8 ppm.
[src:styx-rule/boron] When this content exceeds 2.0 ppm, few plants will perform well and some may not survive.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some boron-containing antibiotics exist in nature.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The first one found was boromycin, isolated from streptomyces in the 1960s.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Others are tartrolons, a group of antibiotics discovered in the 1990s from culture broth of the myxobacterium-group *Sorangium cellulosum*.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In 2013, chemist and synthetic biologist Steve Benner suggested that the conditions on Mars three billion years ago were much more favorable to the stability of RNA and formation of oxygen-containing boron and molybdenum catalysts found in life.
[src:styx-rule/boron] According to Benner's theory, primitive life, which is widely believed to have originated from RNA, first formed on Mars before migrating to Earth.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It is thought that boron plays several essential roles in animals, including humans, but the exact physiological role is poorly understood.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron deficiency has only been clearly established in livestock.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In humans, boron deficiency may affect bone mineral density, though it has been noted that additional research on the effects of bone health is necessary.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is not classified as an essential human nutrient because research has not established a clear biological function for it.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Food and Nutrition Board (FNB) found the existing data insufficient to derive a Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA), Adequate Intake (AI), or Estimated Average Requirement (EAR) for boron and the U.S.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has not established a daily value for boron for food and dietary supplement labeling purposes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] While low boron levels can be detrimental to health, with studies suggesting that they increase the risks of osteoporosis, poor immune function, and cognitive decline, high boron levels are associated with cell damage and toxicity.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Still, studies suggest that boron may exert beneficial effects on reproduction and development, calcium metabolism, bone formation, brain function, insulin and energy substrate metabolism, immunity, and steroid hormone (including estrogen), and vitamin D function, among other functions.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In a small human trial published in 1987 reported on postmenopausal women first made boron deficient and then repleted with 3 mg/day, boron supplementation markedly reduced urinary calcium excretion and elevated the serum concentrations of 17 β-estradiol and testosterone.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Environmental boron appears to be inversely correlated with arthritis.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The exact mechanism by which boron exerts its physiological effects is not fully understood but may involve interactions with adenosine monophosphate (ADP) and *S*-adenosyl methionine (SAM-e), two compounds involved in important cellular functions.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Furthermore, boron appears to inhibit cyclic ADP-ribose, thereby affecting the release of calcium ions from the endoplasmic reticulum and affecting various biological processes.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some studies suggest that boron may reduce levels of inflammatory biomarkers.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Congenital endothelial dystrophy type 2, a rare form of corneal dystrophy, is linked to mutations in SLC4A11 gene that encodes a transporter reportedly regulating the intracellular concentration of boron.
[src:styx-rule/boron] In humans, boron is usually consumed with food that contains boron, such as fruits, leafy vegetables, and nuts.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Foods that are particularly rich in boron include avocados, dried fruits such as raisins, peanuts, pecans, prune juice, grape juice, wine and chocolate powder.
[src:styx-rule/boron] According to 2-day food records from the respondents to the Third National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES III), adult dietary intake was recorded at 0.9 to 1.4 mg/day.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Elemental boron, boron oxide, boric acid, borate, and many organoboron compounds are relatively nontoxic to humans and animals (with toxicity similar to that of table salt).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The LD50 (dose at which there is 50% mortality) for animals is about 6 g per kg of body weight.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Substances with an LD50 above 2 g/kg are considered nontoxic.
[src:styx-rule/boron] An intake of 4 g/day of boric acid was reported without incident, but more than this is considered toxic in more than a few doses.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Intakes of more than 0.5 grams per day for 50 days cause minor digestive and other problems suggestive of toxicity.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boric acid is more toxic to insects than to mammals, and is routinely used as an insecticide.
[src:styx-rule/boron] However, it has been used in neutron capture therapy alongside other boron compounds such as sodium borocaptate and boronophenylalanine with reported low toxicity levels.
[src:styx-rule/boron] The boranes (boron hydrogen compounds) and similar gaseous compounds are quite poisonous.
[src:styx-rule/boron] As usual, boron is not an element that is intrinsically poisonous, but the toxicity of these compounds depends on structure (for another example of this phenomenon, see phosphine).
[src:styx-rule/boron] The boranes are also highly flammable and require special care when handling.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Some combinations of boranes and other compounds are highly explosive.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Sodium borohydride presents a fire hazard owing to its reducing nature and the liberation of hydrogen on contact with acid.
[src:styx-rule/boron] Boron is necessary for plant growth, but an excess of boron is toxic to plants, and occurs particularly in acidic soil.
[src:styx-rule/boron] It presents as a yellowing from the tip inwards of the oldest leaves and black spots in barley leaves, but it can be confused with other stresses such as magnesium deficiency in other plants.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] These are limited to a single typographic line of symbols, which may include subscripts and superscripts.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A chemical formula is not a chemical name since it does not contain any words.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Although a chemical formula may imply certain simple chemical structures, it is not the same as a full chemical structural formula.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae can fully specify the structure of only the simplest of molecules and chemical substances, and are generally more limited in power than chemical names and structural formulae.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The simplest types of chemical formulae are called *empirical formulae*, which use letters and numbers indicating the numerical *proportions* of atoms of each type.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] **Molecular formulae** indicate the simple numbers of each type of atom in a molecule, with no information on structure.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula for glucose is CH2O (twice as many hydrogen atoms as carbon and oxygen), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (12 hydrogen atoms, six carbon and oxygen atoms).
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This is possible if the relevant bonding is easy to show in one dimension.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] An example is the condensed molecular/chemical formula for ethanol, which is CH3−CH2−OH or CH3CH2OH.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, even a condensed chemical formula is necessarily limited in its ability to show complex bonding relationships between atoms, especially atoms that have bonds to four or more different substituents.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For reasons of structural complexity, a single condensed chemical formula (or semi-structural formula) may correspond to different molecules, known as isomers.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, glucose shares its molecular formula C6H12O6 with a number of other sugars, including fructose, galactose and mannose.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Linear equivalent chemical *names* exist that can and do specify uniquely any complex structural formula (see chemical nomenclature), but such names must use many terms (words), rather than the simple element symbols, numbers, and simple typographical symbols that define a chemical formula.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae may be used in chemical equations to describe chemical reactions and other chemical transformations, such as the dissolving of ionic compounds into solution.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A chemical formula identifies each constituent element by its chemical symbol and indicates the proportionate number of atoms of each element.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In empirical formulae, these proportions begin with a key element and then assign numbers of atoms of the other elements in the compound, by ratios to the key element.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For molecular compounds, these ratio numbers can all be expressed as whole numbers.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula of ethanol may be written C2H6O because the molecules of ethanol all contain two carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Some types of ionic compounds, however, cannot be written with entirely whole-number empirical formulae.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] An example is boron carbide, whose formula of CB*n* is a variable non-whole number ratio with n ranging from over 4 to more than 6.5.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] When the chemical compound of the formula consists of simple molecules, chemical formulae often employ ways to suggest the structure of the molecule.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] These types of formulae are variously known as *molecular formulae* and *condensed formulae*.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A molecular formula enumerates the number of atoms to reflect those in the molecule, so that the molecular formula for glucose is C6H12O6 rather than the glucose empirical formula, which is CH2O.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, except for very simple substances, molecular chemical formulae lack needed structural information, and are ambiguous.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For simple molecules, a condensed (or semi-structural) formula is a type of chemical formula that may fully imply a correct structural formula.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, ethanol may be represented by the condensed chemical formula CH3CH2OH, and dimethyl ether by the condensed formula CH3OCH3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] These two molecules have the same empirical and molecular formulae (C2H6O), but may be differentiated by the condensed formulae shown, which are sufficient to represent the full structure of these simple organic compounds.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Condensed chemical formulae may also be used to represent ionic compounds that do not exist as discrete molecules, but nonetheless do contain covalently bound clusters within them.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] These polyatomic ions are groups of atoms that are covalently bound together and have an overall ionic charge, such as the sulfate [SO4]2− ion.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Each polyatomic ion in a compound is written individually in order to illustrate the separate groupings.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, the compound dichlorine hexoxide has an empirical formula ClO3, and molecular formula Cl2O6, but in liquid or solid forms, this compound is more correctly shown by an ionic condensed formula [ClO2]+[ClO4]−, which illustrates that this compound consists of [ClO2]+ ions and [ClO4]− ions.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In such cases, the condensed formula only need be complex enough to show at least one of each ionic species.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae as described here are distinct from the far more complex chemical systematic names that are used in various systems of chemical nomenclature.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This name, interpreted by the rules behind it, fully specifies glucose's structural formula, but the name is not a chemical formula as usually understood, and uses terms and words not used in chemical formulae.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Such names, unlike basic formulae, may be able to represent full structural formulae without graphs.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In chemistry, the empirical formula of a chemical is a simple expression of the relative number of each type of atom or ratio of the elements in the compound.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Empirical formulae are the standard for ionic compounds, such as CaCl2, and for macromolecules, such as SiO2.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] An empirical formula makes no reference to isomerism, structure, or absolute number of atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The term *empirical* refers to the process of elemental analysis, a technique of analytical chemistry used to determine the relative percent composition of a pure chemical substance by element.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, hexane has a molecular formula of C6H14, and (for one of its isomers, n-hexane) a structural formula CH3CH2CH2CH2CH2CH3, implying that it has a chain structure of 6 carbon atoms, and 14 hydrogen atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, the empirical formula for hexane is C3H7.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Likewise the empirical formula for hydrogen peroxide, H2O2, is simply HO, expressing the 1:1 ratio of component elements.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Formaldehyde and acetic acid have the same empirical formula, CH2O.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This is also the molecular formula for formaldehyde, but acetic acid has double the number of atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Like the other formula types detailed below, an empirical formula shows the number of elements in a molecule, and determines whether it is a binary compound, ternary compound, quaternary compound, or has even more elements.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Molecular formulae simply indicate the numbers of each type of atom in a molecule of a molecular substance.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] They are the same as empirical formulae for molecules that only have one atom of a particular type, but otherwise may have larger numbers.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] An example of the difference is the empirical formula for glucose, which is CH2O (*ratio* 1:2:1), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (*number of atoms* 6:12:6).
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A molecular formula provides more information about a molecule than its empirical formula, but is more difficult to establish.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In addition to indicating the number of atoms of each elementa molecule, a structural formula indicates how the atoms are organized, and shows (or implies) the chemical bonds between the atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] There are multiple types of structural formulas focused on different aspects of the molecular structure.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The two diagrams show two molecules which are structural isomers of each other, since they both have the same molecular formula C4H10, but they have different structural formulas as shown.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The connectivity of a molecule often has a strong influence on its physical and chemical properties and behavior.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Two molecules composed of the same numbers of the same types of atoms (i.e. a pair of isomers) might have completely different chemical and/or physical properties if the atoms are connected differently or in different positions.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In such cases, a structural formula is useful, as it illustrates which atoms are bonded to which other ones.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] From the connectivity, it is often possible to deduce the approximate shape of the molecule.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A condensed (or semi-structural) formula may represent the types and spatial arrangement of bonds in a simple chemical substance, though it does not necessarily specify isomers or complex structures.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, ethane consists of two carbon atoms single-bonded to each other, with each carbon atom having three hydrogen atoms bonded to it.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Its chemical formula can be rendered as CH3CH3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In ethylene there is a double bond between the carbon atoms (and thus each carbon only has two hydrogens), therefore the chemical formula may be written: CH2CH2, and the fact that there is a double bond between the carbons is implicit because carbon has a valence of four.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, a more explicit method is to write H2C=CH2 or less commonly H2C::CH2.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The two lines (or two pairs of dots) indicate that a double bond connects the atoms on either side of them.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A triple bond may be expressed with three lines (HC≡CH) or three pairs of dots (HC:::CH), and if there may be ambiguity, a single line or pair of dots may be used to indicate a single bond.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Molecules with multiple functional groups that are the same may be expressed by enclosing the repeated group in round brackets.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, isobutane may be written (CH3)3CH.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This condensed structural formula implies a different connectivity from other molecules that can be formed using the same atoms in the same proportions (isomers).
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The formula (CH3)3CH implies a central carbon atom connected to one hydrogen atom and three methyl groups (CH3).
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The same number of atoms of each element (10 hydrogens and 4 carbons, or C4H10) may be used to make a straight chain molecule, *n*-butane: CH3CH2CH2CH3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The International Union of Crystallography (IUCr) has proposed a crystal-chemical formula notation that extends standard formulae with optional annotations for these items.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The alkene called but-2-ene has two isomers, which the chemical formula CH3CH=CHCH3 does not identify.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The relative position of the two methyl groups must be indicated by additional notation denoting whether the methyl groups are on the same side of the double bond (*cis* or *Z*) or on the opposite sides from each other (*trans* or *E*).
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] As noted above, in order to represent the full structural formulae of many complex organic and inorganic compounds, chemical nomenclature may be needed which goes well beyond the available resources used above in simple condensed formulae.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] See IUPAC nomenclature of organic chemistry and IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry 2005 for examples.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In addition, linear naming systems such as International Chemical Identifier (InChI) allow a computer to construct a structural formula, and simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) allows a more human-readable ASCII input.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, all these nomenclature systems go beyond the standards of chemical formulae, and technically are chemical naming systems, not formula systems.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For polymers in condensed chemical formulae, parentheses are placed around the repeating unit.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, a hydrocarbon molecule that is described as CH3(CH2)50CH3, is a molecule with fifty repeating units.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] If the number of repeating units is unknown or variable, the letter *n* may be used to indicate this formula: CH3(CH2)*n*CH3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For ions, the charge on a particular atom may be denoted with a right-hand superscript.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The total charge on a charged molecule or a polyatomic ion may also be shown in this way, such as for hydronium, H3O+, or sulfate, SO2−4.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Here + and − are used in place of +1 and −1, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For more complex ions, brackets [ ] are often used to enclose the ionic formula, as in [B12H12]2−, which is found in compounds such as caesium dodecaborate, Cs2[B12H12].
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Parentheses ( ) can be nested inside brackets to indicate a repeating unit, as in Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride, [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Here, (NH3)6 indicates that the ion contains six ammine groups (NH3) bonded to cobalt, and [ ] encloses the entire formula of the ion with charge +3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This is strictly optional; a chemical formula is valid with or without ionization information, and Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride may be written as [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3 or [Co(NH3)6]Cl3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Brackets, like parentheses, behave in chemistry as they do in mathematics, grouping terms together – they are not specifically employed only for ionization states.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In the latter case here, the parentheses indicate 6 groups all of the same shape, bonded to another group of size 1 (the cobalt atom), and then the entire bundle, as a group, is bonded to 3 chlorine atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] In the former case, it is clearer that the bond connecting the chlorines is ionic, rather than covalent.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Although isotopes are more relevant to nuclear chemistry or stable isotope chemistry than to conventional chemistry, different isotopes may be indicated with a prefixed superscript in a chemical formula.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, the phosphate ion containing radioactive phosphorus-32 is [32PO4]3−.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Also a study involving stable isotope ratios might include the molecule 18O16O.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A left-hand subscript is sometimes used redundantly to indicate the atomic number.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, 8O2 for dioxygen, and 16 8O 2 for the most abundant isotopic species of dioxygen.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This is convenient when writing equations for nuclear reactions, in order to show the balance of charge more clearly.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The @ symbol (at sign) indicates an atom or molecule trapped inside a cage but not chemically bound to it.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, a buckminsterfullerene (C60) with an atom (M) would simply be represented as MC60 regardless of whether M was inside the fullerene without chemical bonding or outside, bound to one of the carbon atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Using the @ symbol, this would be denoted M@C60 if M was inside the carbon network.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A non-fullerene example is [As@Ni12As20]3−, an ion in which one arsenic (As) atom is trapped in a cage formed by the other 32 atoms.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] This notation was proposed in 1991 with the discovery of fullerene cages (endohedral fullerenes), which can trap atoms such as La to form, for example, La@C60 or La@C82.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The choice of the symbol has been explained by the authors as being concise, readily printed and transmitted electronically (the at sign is included in ASCII, which most modern character encoding schemes are based on), and the visual aspects suggesting the structure of an endohedral fullerene.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae most often use integers for each element.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] However, there is a class of compounds, called non-stoichiometric compounds, that cannot be represented by small integers.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Such a formula might be written using decimal fractions, as in Fe0.95O, or it might include a variable part represented by a letter, as in Fe1−*x*O, where *x* is normally much less than 1.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A chemical formula used for a series of compounds that differ from each other by a constant unit is called a *general formula*.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] It generates a homologous series of chemical formulae.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] For example, alcohols may be represented by the formula C*n*H2*n* + 1OH (*n* ≥ 1), giving the homologs methanol, ethanol, propanol for 1 ≤ *n* ≤ 3.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] When the formula contains no carbon, all the elements, including hydrogen, are listed alphabetically.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] The Hill system was first published by Edwin A.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] Hill of the United States Patent and Trademark Office in 1900.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] It is the most commonly used system in chemical databases and printed indexes to sort lists of compounds.
[src:styx-rule/chemical-formula] A list of formulae in Hill system order is arranged alphabetically, as above, with single-letter elements coming before two-letter symbols when the symbols begin with the same letter (so "B" comes before "Be", which comes before "Br").
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen gas was first produced artificially in the 17th century by the reaction of acids with metals.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Henry Cavendish, in 1766–1781, identified hydrogen gas as a distinct substance and discovered its property of producing water when burned: this is the origin of hydrogen's name, which means 'water-former' (from Ancient Greek: ὕδωρ, romanized: *húdōr*, lit.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] 'water', and γεννάω, *gennáō*, 'I bring forth').
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Understanding the colors of light absorbed and emitted by hydrogen was a crucial part of the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen, typically nonmetallic except under extreme pressure, readily forms covalent bonds with most nonmetals, contributing to the formation of compounds like water and various organic substances.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Its role is crucial in acid–base reactions, which mainly involve proton exchange among soluble molecules.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In ionic compounds, hydrogen can take the form of either a negatively-charged anion, where it is known as hydride, or as a positively charged cation, H+, hydron.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Although tightly bonded to water molecules, hydrons strongly affect the behavior of aqueous solutions, as reflected in the importance of pH.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydride, on the other hand, is rarely observed because it tends to deprotonate solvents, yielding H2.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the early universe, neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years after the Big Bang as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] After stars began to form, most of the hydrogen in the intergalactic medium was re-ionized.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Nearly all hydrogen production is done by transforming fossil fuels, particularly steam reforming of natural gas.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It can also be produced from water or saline by electrolysis, but this process is more expensive.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Its main industrial uses include fossil fuel processing and ammonia production for fertilizer.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Emerging uses for hydrogen include the use of fuel cells to generate electricity.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The ground state energy level of the electron in a hydrogen atom is −13.6 electronvolts (eV), equivalent to an ultraviolet photon of roughly 91 nanometers wavelength.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen are referred to by consecutive quantum numbers, with $n=1$ being the ground state.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The hydrogen spectral series corresponds to emission of light due to transitions from higher to lower energy levels.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Each energy level is further split by spin interactions between the electron and proton into four hyperfine levels.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] High-precision values for the hydrogen atom energy levels are required for definitions of physical constants.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Quantum calculations have identified nine contributions to the energy levels.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The eigenvalue from the Dirac equation is the largest contribution.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Other terms include relativistic recoil, the self-energy, and the vacuum polarization terms.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The standards organization for chemical names, IUPAC, gives general names when the context assumes natural isotope abundance or ignores the isotope.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These general names are *hydrogen* for the neutral atom, *hydron* for the cation, H+, *hydride* for the anion, and H-.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The name *proton* is often used for the positively charged cation, but this is strictly correct only for the cation of the dominant isotope 1 H.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen has three naturally-occurring isotopes, denoted 1 H, 2 H and 3 H.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Other, highly-unstable nuclides (4 H to 7 H) have been synthesized in laboratories but not observed in nature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Unique among the elements, distinct names are assigned to hydrogen's isotopes in common use.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] During the early study of radioactivity, heavy radioisotopes were given their own names, but these are mostly no longer used.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The symbols D and T (instead of 2 H and 3 H) are sometimes used for deuterium and tritium, but the symbol P was already used for phosphorus and thus was not available for protium.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In its nomenclatural guidelines, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) allows any of D, T, 2 H, and 3 H to be used, though 2 H and 3 H are preferred.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Antihydrogen (H) is the antimatter counterpart to hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It consists of an anti­proton with a positron.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The exotic atom muonium (symbol Mu), composed of an antimuon and an electron, is the anti­matter analogue of hydrogen; IUPAC nomenclature incorporates such hypothetical compounds as muonium chloride (MuCl) and sodium muonide (NaMu), analogous to hydrogen chloride and sodium hydride respectively.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Under standard conditions, hydrogen is a gas of diatomic molecules with the formula H2, officially called "dihydrogen", but also called "molecular hydrogen", or simply hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Dihydrogen is a colorless, odorless, flammable gas.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The amount of heat released per mole of hydrogen is −286 kilojoules (kJ), or 141.9 megajoules (MJ) for a one-kilogram (2.2 lb) mass (based on the higher heating value measurement).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen gas forms explosive mixtures with air in concentrations from 4%–74% and with chlorine at 5%–95%.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The hydrogen autoignition temperature, the temperature of spontaneous ignition in air, is 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In a high-pressure hydrogen leak, the shock wave from the leak itself can heat air to the autoignition temperature, leading to flaming and possibly explosion.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen flames emit faint blue and ultraviolet light.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Flame detectors are used to detect hydrogen fires as they are nearly invisible to the naked eye in daylight.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Molecular H2 exists as two nuclear isomers that differ in the spin states of their nuclei.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the **ortho­hydrogen** form, the spins of the two nuclei are parallel, forming a spin triplet state having a total molecular spin $S=1$ ; in the **para­hydrogen** form the spins are anti­parallel and form a spin singlet state having spin $S=0$ .
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The equilibrium ratio of ortho- to para-hydrogen depends on temperature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] At room temperature or warmer, equilibrium hydrogen gas contains about 25% of the para form and 75% of the ortho form.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The ortho form is an excited state, having higher energy than the para form by 1.455 kJ/mol, and it converts to the para form over the course of several minutes when cooled to low temperature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The thermal properties of these isomers differ because each has distinct rotational quantum states.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The ortho-to-para ratio in H2 is an important consideration in the liquefaction and storage of liquid hydrogen: the conversion from ortho to para is exothermic, and produces sufficient heat to evaporate most of the liquid if the conversion to para­hydrogen does not occur during the cooling process.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Catalysts for the ortho-para inter­conversion, such as ferric oxide and activated carbon compounds, are therefore used during hydrogen cooling to avoid this loss of liquid.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen can exist at temperatures below hydrogen's critical point of 33 kelvins (−240.2 °C; −400.3 °F).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] However, for it to be in a fully liquid state at atmospheric pressure, H2 needs to be cooled to 20.28 K (−252.87 °C; −423.17 °F).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen becomes solid hydrogen at standard pressure below hydrogen's melting point of 14.01 K (−259.14 °C; −434.45 °F).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Distinct solid phases exist, known as Phase I through Phase V, each exhibiting a characteristic molecular arrangement.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Liquid and solid phases can exist in combination at the triple point; this mixture is known as slush hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Metallic hydrogen, a phase obtained at extremely high pressures (in excess of 400 billion Pa (58,000,000 psi)), is an electrical conductor.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It is believed to exist deep within giant planets like Jupiter.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] When ionized, hydrogen becomes a plasma.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This is the form in which hydrogen exists within stars.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In 1671, Irish scientist Robert Boyle discovered and described the reaction between iron filings and dilute acids, which results in the production of hydrogen gas.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Boyle did not note that the gas was flammable, but hydrogen would play a key role in overturning the phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In 1766, Henry Cavendish was the first to recognize hydrogen gas as a discrete substance, by naming the gas from a metal-acid reaction "inflammable air".
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] He speculated that "inflammable air" was in fact identical to the hypothetical substance "phlogiston" and further finding in 1781 that the gas produces water when burned.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] He is usually given credit for the discovery of hydrogen as an element.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In 1783, Antoine Lavoisier identified the element that came to be known as hydrogen when he and Laplace reproduced Cavendish's finding that water is produced when hydrogen is burned.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Lavoisier produced hydrogen for his experiments on mass conservation by treating metallic iron with a stream of water through an incandescent iron tube heated in a fire.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Many metals react similarly with water, leading to the production of hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In some situations, this H2-producing process is problematic, for instance in the case of zirconium cladding on nuclear fuel rods.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] By 1806 hydrogen was used to fill balloons.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] François Isaac de Rivaz built the first de Rivaz engine, an internal combustion engine powered by a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen, in 1806.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Edward Daniel Clarke invented the hydrogen gas blowpipe in 1819.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The Döbereiner's lamp and limelight were invented in 1823.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied for the first time by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] He produced solid hydrogen the next year.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] According to quantum theory, this behavior arises from the spacing of the (quantized) rotational energy levels, which are particularly wide-spaced in H2 because of its low mass.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These widely-spaced levels inhibit equal partition of heat energy into rotational motion in hydrogen at low temperatures.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Diatomic gases composed of heavier atoms do not have such widely spaced levels and do not exhibit the same effect.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The existence of the hydride anion was suggested by Gilbert N.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Lewis in 1916 for group 1 and group 2 salt-like compounds.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In 1920, Moers electrolyzed molten lithium hydride (LiH), producing a stoichiometric quantity of hydrogen at the anode.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Because of its simple atomic structure, consisting only of a proton and an electron, the hydrogen atom, together with the spectrum of light produced from it or absorbed by it, has been central to the development of the theory of atomic structure.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen can be calculated fairly accurately using the Bohr model of the atom, in which the electron "orbits" the proton, just as Earth orbits the Sun.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] However, the electron and proton are held together by electrostatic attraction, while planets and celestial objects are held by gravity.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Due to the discretization of angular momentum postulated in early quantum mechanics by Bohr, the electron in the Bohr model can only occupy certain allowed distances from the proton, and therefore only certain allowed energies.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen's unique position as the only neutral atom for which the Schrödinger equation can be directly solved has significantly contributed to the understanding of quantum mechanics through the exploration of its energetics.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Furthermore, study of the corresponding simplicity of the hydrogen molecule and the corresponding cation, H+2, brought understanding of the nature of the chemical bond, which followed shortly after the quantum mechanical treatment of the hydrogen atom had been developed in the mid-1920s.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Because H2 has only 7% the density of air, it was once widely used as a lifting gas in balloons and airships.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The first hydrogen-filled balloon was invented by Jacques Charles in 1783.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen provided the lift for the first reliable form of air-travel following the 1852 invention of the first hydrogen-lifted airship by Henri Giffard.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] German count Ferdinand von Zeppelin promoted the idea of rigid airships lifted by hydrogen that later were called Zeppelins, the first of which had its maiden flight in 1900.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Regularly-scheduled flights started in 1910 and by the outbreak of World War I in August 1914, they had carried 35,000 passengers without a serious incident.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen-lifted airships in the form of blimps were used as observation platforms and bombers during World War II, especially on the US Eastern seaboard.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The first non-stop transatlantic crossing was made by the British airship *R34* in 1919 and regular passenger service resumed in the 1920s.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen was used in the *Hindenburg*, which caught fire over New Jersey on 6 May 1937.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The hydrogen that filled the airship was ignited, possibly by static electricity, and burst into flames.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Following this disaster, commercial hydrogen airship travel ceased.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is still used, in preference to non-flammable but more expensive helium, as a lifting gas for weather balloons.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Deuterium was discovered in December 1931 by Harold Urey, and tritium was prepared in 1934 by Ernest Rutherford, Mark Oliphant, and Paul Harteck.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Heavy water, which consists of deuterium in the place of regular hydrogen, was discovered by Urey's group in 1932.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The thermodynamic basis of this low reactivity is the very strong H–H bond, with a bond dissociation energy of 435.7 kJ/mol.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It does form coordination complexes called dihydrogen complexes.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These species provide insights into the early steps in the interactions of hydrogen with metal catalysts.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] According to neutron diffraction, the metal and two H atoms form a triangle in these complexes.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The H-H bond remains intact but is elongated.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Although exotic on Earth, the H+3 ion is common in the universe.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It is a triangular species, like the aforementioned dihydrogen complexes.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It is known as protonated molecular hydrogen or the trihydrogen cation.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen reacts with chlorine to produce HCl, and with bromine to produce HBr, via a chain reaction.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For example, in the case of Br2, the dibromine molecule is split apart: Br2 + (UV light) → 2Br•.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The addition of H2 to unsaturated organic compounds, such as alkenes and alkynes, is called hydrogenation.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Even if the reaction is energetically favorable, it does not occur spontaneously even at higher temperatures.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the presence of a catalyst like finely divided platinum or nickel, the reaction proceeds at room temperature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen can exist in both +1 and −1 oxidation states, forming compounds through ionic and covalent bonding.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The element is part of a wide range of substances, including water, hydrocarbons, and numerous other organic compounds.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The H+ ion—commonly referred to as a proton due to its single proton and absence of electrons—is central to acid–base chemistry, although the proton does not move freely.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the Brønsted–Lowry framework, acids are defined by their ability to donate H+ ions to bases.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen forms a vast variety of compounds with carbon, known as hydrocarbons, and an even greater diversity with other elements (heteroatoms), giving rise to the broad class of organic compounds often associated with living organisms.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen compounds with hydrogen in the oxidation state −1 are known as hydrides, which are usually formed between hydrogen and metals.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The hydrides can be ionic (aka saline), covalent, or metallic.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] With heating, H2 reacts efficiently with the alkali and alkaline earth metals to give the ionic hydrides of the formulas MH and MH2, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These salt-like crystalline compounds have high melting points and all react with water to liberate hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Covalent hydrides include boranes and polymeric aluminium hydride.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Transition metals form metal hydrides via continuous dissolution of hydrogen into the metal.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] A well-known hydride is lithium aluminium hydride: the [AlH4]− anion carries hydridic centers firmly attached to the Al(III).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Perhaps the most extensive series of hydrides are the boranes, compounds consisting only of boron and hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrides can bond to these electropositive elements not only as a terminal ligand but also as bridging ligands.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In diborane (B2H6), four hydrogen atoms are terminal, while two bridge between the two boron atoms.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] When bonded to a more electronegative element, particularly fluorine, oxygen, or nitrogen, hydrogen can participate in a form of medium-strength noncovalent bonding with another electronegative element with a lone pair like oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This phenomenon, called hydrogen bonding, is critical to the stability of many biological molecules.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen bonding alters molecule structures, viscosity, solubility, melting and boiling points, and even protein folding dynamics.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In water, hydrogen bonding plays an important role in reaction thermodynamics.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] A hydrogen bond can shift over to proton transfer.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Under the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, acids are proton donors, while bases are proton acceptors.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] A bare proton (H+) essentially cannot exist in anything other than a vacuum.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Otherwise it attaches to other atoms, ions, or molecules.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Even chemical species as inert as methane can be protonated.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The term "proton" is used loosely and metaphorically to refer to solvated hydrogen cations attached to other chemical species; it is denoted "H+" without any implication that any single protons exist freely in solution as a species.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] To avoid the implication of the naked proton in solution, acidic aqueous solutions are sometimes considered to contain the "hydronium ion" ([H3O]+), or still more accurately, [H9O4]+.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Other oxonium ions are found when water is in acidic solution with other solvents.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The concentration of these solvated protons determines the pH of a solution, a logarithmic scale that reflects its acidity or basicity.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Lower pH values indicate higher concentrations of hydronium ions, corresponding to more acidic conditions.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen, as atomic H, is the most abundant chemical element in the universe, making up 75% of normal matter by mass. and >90% by number of atoms.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the early universe, protons formed in the first second after the Big Bang; neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years later during the recombination epoch as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In astrophysics, neutral hydrogen in the interstellar medium is called *H I* and ionized hydrogen is called *H II*.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Radiation from stars ionizes H I to H II, creating spheres of ionized H II around stars.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the chronology of the universe neutral hydrogen dominated until the birth of stars during the era of reionization, which then produced bubbles of ionized hydrogen that grew and merged over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These are the source of the 21-centimeter hydrogen line, at 1420 MHz, that is detected in order to probe primordial hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The large amount of neutral hydrogen found in the damped Lyman-alpha systems is thought to dominate the cosmological baryonic density of the universe up to a redshift of *z* = 4.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is found in great abundance in stars and gas giant planets.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Molecular clouds of H2 are associated with star formation.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen plays a vital role in powering stars through the proton-proton reaction in lower-mass stars, and through the CNO cycle of nuclear fusion in stars more massive than the Sun.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Protonated molecular hydrogen (H+3) is found in the interstellar medium, where it is generated by ionization of molecular hydrogen by cosmic rays.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This ion has also been observed in the upper atmosphere of Jupiter.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The ion is long-lived in outer space due to the low temperature and density.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] H+3 is one of the most abundant ions in the universe, and it plays a notable role in the chemistry of the interstellar medium.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Neutral triatomic hydrogen H3 can exist only in an excited form and is unstable.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is the third most abundant element on the Earth's surface, mostly existing within chemical compounds such as hydrocarbons and water.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Elemental hydrogen is normally in the form of a gas, H2, at standard conditions.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It is present in a very low concentration in Earth's atmosphere (around 0.53 parts per million on a molar basis) because of its light weight, which enables it to escape the atmosphere more rapidly than heavier gases.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Despite its low concentration in the atmosphere, terrestrial hydrogen is sufficiently abundant to support the metabolism of several varieties of bacteria.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Large underground deposits of hydrogen gas have been discovered in several countries including Mali, France and Australia.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] As of 2024, it is uncertain how much underground hydrogen can be extracted economically.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Nearly all of the world's current supply of hydrogen gas (H2) is produced from fossil fuels, with less than 1% of hydrogen being produced by low-emissions technologies in 2025.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Many methods exist for producing H2, but three dominate commercially: steam reforming often coupled to water-gas shift, partial oxidation of hydrocarbons, and water electrolysis.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is mainly produced by steam methane reforming (SMR), the reaction of water and methane.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Producing one tonne of hydrogen through this process emits 6.6–9.3 tonnes of carbon dioxide.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The production of natural gas feedstock also produces emissions such as vented and fugitive methane, which further contributes to the overall carbon footprint of hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This reaction is favored at low pressures but is nonetheless conducted at high pressures (2.0 MPa [20 atm; 590 inHg]) because high-pressure H2 is the most marketable product, and pressure swing adsorption (PSA) purification systems work better at higher pressures.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The product mixture is known as "synthesis gas" because it is often used directly for the production of methanol and many other compounds.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrocarbons other than methane can be used to produce synthesis gas with varying product ratios.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Therefore, steam reforming typically employs an excess of H2O.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Additional hydrogen can be recovered from the steam by using carbon monoxide through the water gas shift reaction (WGS).
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is sometimes produced and consumed in the same industrial process, without being separated.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the Haber process for ammonia production, hydrogen is generated from natural gas.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Olefin production units may produce substantial quantities of byproduct hydrogen, particularly from cracking light feedstocks like ethane or propane.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Electrolysis of water is a conceptually simple method of producing hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Commercial electrolyzers use nickel-based catalysts in strongly alkaline solution.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Platinum is a better catalyst but is expensive.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The hydrogen created through electrolysis using renewable energy is commonly referred to as "green hydrogen".
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Electrolysis of brine to yield chlorine also produces high-purity hydrogen as a co-product, which is used for a variety of transformations such as hydrogenations.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The electrolysis process is more expensive than producing hydrogen from methane without carbon capture and storage.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Innovation in hydrogen electrolyzers could make large-scale production of hydrogen from electricity more cost-competitive.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The carbon may be sold as a manufacturing feedstock or fuel, or landfilled.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This route could have a lower carbon footprint than existing hydrogen production processes, but mechanisms for removing the carbon and preventing it from reacting with the catalyst remain obstacles for industrial-scale use.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Water splitting is the process by which water is decomposed into its components.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The reaction occurs in the light-dependent reactions in all photosynthetic organisms.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] A few organisms, including the alga *Chlamydomonas reinhardtii* and cyanobacteria, have evolved a second step in the dark reactions in which protons and electrons are reduced to form H2 gas by specialized hydrogenases in the chloroplast.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Efforts have been undertaken to genetically modify cyanobacterial hydrogenases to more efficiently generate H2 gas even in the presence of oxygen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Efforts have also been undertaken with genetically‐modified alga in a bioreactor.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Over 200 thermochemical cycles can be used for water splitting.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] A number of labs (including in France, Germany, Greece, Japan, and the United States) are developing thermochemical methods to produce hydrogen from solar energy and water.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] H2 is produced in organisms by enzymes called hydrogenases.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This process allows the host organism to use fermentation as a source of energy.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These same enzymes also can oxidize H2, such that the host organisms can subsist by reducing oxidized substrates using electrons extracted from H2.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogenase enzymes feature iron or iron–nickel centers at their active sites.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The natural cycle of hydrogen production and consumption by organisms is called the hydrogen cycle.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Some bacteria such as *Mycobacterium smegmatis* can use the small amount of hydrogen in the atmosphere as a source of energy when other sources are lacking.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Their hydrogenases feature small channels that exclude oxygen from the active site, permitting the reaction to occur even though the hydrogen concentration is very low and the oxygen concentration is as in normal air.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Confirming the existence of hydrogenase‐employing microbes in the human gut, H2 occurs in human breath.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The concentration in the breath of fasting people at rest is typically under 5 parts per million (ppm), but can reach 50 ppm when people with intestinal disorders consume molecules they cannot absorb during diagnostic hydrogen breath tests.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Serpentinization is a geological mechanism which produces highly-reducing conditions.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This process also is relevant to the corrosion of iron and steel in oxygen-free groundwater and in reducing soils below the water table.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is also often a by-product of other reactions.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Many metals react with water to produce H2, but the rate of hydrogen evolution depends on the metal, the pH, and the presence of alloying agents.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Most often, hydrogen evolution is induced by acids.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The alkali and alkaline earth metals as well as aluminium, zinc, manganese, and iron, react readily with aqueous acids.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Many metals, such as aluminium, are slow to react with water because they form passivated oxide coatings.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] An alloy of aluminium and gallium, however, does react with water.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] If H2 is to be used as an energy source, its storage is important.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For example, at room temperature and 0.1 millipascals (9.9×10−10 atm), approx.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] 0.05 moles of hydrogen dissolve into one kilogram (2.2 lb) of diethyl ether.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] H2 can be stored in compressed form, although compressing costs energy.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Liquefaction is impractical given hydrogen's low critical temperature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In contrast, ammonia and many hydrocarbons can be liquified at room temperature under pressure.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For these reasons, hydrogen *carriers*—materials that reversibly bind H2—have attracted much attention.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The key question is then the weight percent of H2-equivalents within the carrier material.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For example, hydrogen can be reversibly absorbed into many rare earths and transition metals and is soluble in both nanocrystalline and amorphous metals.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen solubility in metals is influenced by local distortions or impurities in the crystal lattice.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] These properties may be useful when hydrogen is purified by passage through hot palladium disks, but the gas's high solubility is also a metallurgical problem, contributing to the embrittlement of many metals, complicating the design of pipelines and storage tanks.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The most problematic aspect of metal hydrides for storage is their modest H2 content, often on the order of 1%.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For this reason, there is interest in storage of H2 in compounds of low molecular weight.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For example, ammonia borane (H3N−BH3) contains 19.8 weight percent of H2.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The problem with this material is that after release of H2, the resulting boron nitride does not re-add H2: i.e., ammonia borane is an irreversible hydrogen carrier.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Large quantities of H2 are used in the "upgrading" of fossil fuels.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Key consumers of H2 include hydrodesulfurization and hydrocracking.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Many of these reactions can be classified as hydrogenolysis, i.e., the cleavage of bonds by hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogenation, the addition of H2 to various substrates, is done on a large scale.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] This process consumes a few percent of the energy budget in the entire industry and is the biggest consumer of hydrogen.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The resulting ammonia is used extensively in fertilizer production; these fertilizers have become essential feedstocks in modern agriculture.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogenation is also used to convert unsaturated fats and oils to saturated fats and oils.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The major application is the production of margarine.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Methanol is produced by hydrogenation of carbon dioxide; the mixture of hydrogen and carbon dioxide used for this process is known as syngas.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It is similarly the source of hydrogen in the manufacture of hydrochloric acid.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] H2 is also used as a reducing agent for the conversion of some ores to the metals.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The potential for using hydrogen (H2) as a fuel has been widely discussed.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen can be used in fuel cells to produce electricity, or burned to generate heat.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] When hydrogen is consumed in fuel cells, the only emission at the point of use is water vapor.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] When burned, hydrogen produces relatively little pollution at the point of combustion, but can lead to thermal formation of harmful nitrogen oxides.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] If hydrogen is produced with low or zero greenhouse gas emissions (green hydrogen), it can play a significant role in decarbonizing energy systems where there are challenges and limitations to replacing fossil fuels with direct use of electricity.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen fuel can produce the intense heat required for industrial production of steel, cement, glass, and chemicals, thus contributing to the decarbonization of industry alongside other technologies, such as electric arc furnaces for steelmaking.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] However, it is likely to play a larger role in providing industrial feedstock for cleaner production of ammonia and organic chemicals.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen used to decarbonize transportation is likely to find its largest applications in shipping, aviation and, to a lesser extent, heavy goods vehicles, through the use of hydrogen-derived synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol and fuel cell technology.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] For light-duty vehicles including cars, hydrogen is far behind other alternative fuel vehicles, especially compared with the rate of adoption of battery electric vehicles, and may not play a significant role in future.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen together serve as cryogenic propellants in liquid-propellant rockets, as in the Space Shuttle main engines.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] NASA has investigated the use of rocket propellant made from atomic hydrogen, boron or carbon that is frozen into solid molecular hydrogen particles suspended in liquid helium.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Upon warming, the mixture vaporizes to allow the atomic species to recombine, heating the mixture to high temperature.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen produced when there is a surplus of variable renewable electricity could in principle be stored and later used to generate heat or to re-generate electricity.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] It can be further transformed into synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Disadvantages of hydrogen fuel include high costs of storage and distribution due to hydrogen's explosivity, its large volume compared to other fuels, and its tendency to embrittle materials.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The economic disadvantage of distribution can be reduced by co-locating facilities that use hydrogen in mining industry hubs.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The very long-lived, rechargeable nickel–hydrogen battery developed for satellite power systems uses pressurized gaseous H2.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The International Space Station, Mars Odyssey and the Mars Global Surveyor are equipped with nickel-hydrogen batteries.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In the dark part of its orbit, the Hubble Space Telescope is also powered by nickel-hydrogen batteries, which were finally replaced in May 2009, more than 19 years after launch and 13 years beyond their design life.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is employed in semiconductor manufacturing to saturate broken ("dangling") bonds of amorphous silicon and amorphous carbon, which helps in stabilizing the materials' properties.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen, introduced as an unintended side-effect of production, acts as a shallow electron donor leading to n-type conductivity in ZnO, with important uses in transducers and phosphors.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Detailed analysis of ZnO and of MgO shows evidence of four and six-fold hydrogen multicentre bonds.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] The doping behavior of hydrogen varies with material.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In hydrogen pipelines and steel storage vessels, hydrogen molecules are prone to reacting with metals, causing hydrogen embrittlement and leaks in the pipeline or storage vessel.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Since it is lighter than air, hydrogen does not easily accumulate to form a combustible gas mixture.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] However, even without ignition sources, high-pressure hydrogen leakage may cause spontaneous combustion and detonation.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is flammable when mixed even in small amounts with air.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Ignition can occur at a volumetric ratio of hydrogen to air as low as 4%.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] In approximately 70% of hydrogen ignition accidents, the ignition source cannot be determined.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen fire, while being extremely hot, is almost invisible to the human eye, and thus can lead to accidental burns.
[src:styx-rule/hydrogen] Hydrogen is non-toxic, but like most gases it can cause asphyxiation in the absence of adequate ventilation.
[src:styx-rule/integer] An **integer** is the number zero (0), a positive natural number (1, 2, 3, ...), or the negation of a positive natural number (−1, −2, −3, ...).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The negations or additive inverses of the positive natural numbers are referred to as **negative integers**.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The set of all integers is often denoted by the boldface **Z** or blackboard bold ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The set of natural numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is a subset of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, which in turn is a subset of the set of all rational numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠, itself a subset of the real numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Like the set of natural numbers, the set of integers ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is countably infinite.
[src:styx-rule/integer] An integer may be regarded as a real number that can be written without a fractional component.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The integers form the smallest group and the smallest ring containing the natural numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] In algebraic number theory, integers are sometimes called **rational integers** to distinguish them from the more general algebraic integers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] In fact, (rational) integers are algebraic integers that are also rational numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The word integer comes from the Latin *integer* meaning "whole" or (literally) "untouched", from *in* ("not") plus *tangere* ("to touch").
[src:styx-rule/integer] "Entire" derives from the same origin via the French word *entier*, which means both *entire* and *integer*.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Historically the term was used for a number that was a multiple of 1, or to the whole part of a mixed number.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Only positive integers were considered, making the term synonymous with the natural numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The definition of integer expanded over time to include negative numbers as their usefulness was recognized.
[src:styx-rule/integer] For example Leonhard Euler in his 1765 *Elements of Algebra* defined integers to include both positive and negative numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The phrase *the set of the integers* was not used before the end of the 19th century, when Georg Cantor introduced the concept of infinite sets and set theory.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The use of the letter Z to denote the set of integers comes from the German word *Zahlen* ("numbers") and has been attributed to David Hilbert.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The earliest known use of the notation in a textbook occurs in Algèbre written by the collective Nicolas Bourbaki, dating to 1947.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The notation was not adopted immediately.
[src:styx-rule/integer] For example, another textbook used the letter J, and a 1960 paper used Z to denote the non-negative integers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] But by 1961, Z was generally used by modern algebra texts to denote the positive and negative integers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Some authors use ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} ^{*}$ ⁠ for non-zero integers, while others use it for non-negative integers, or for {−1,1} (the group of units of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠).
[src:styx-rule/integer] Additionally, ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ ⁠ is used to denote either the set of integers modulo *p* (i.e., the set of congruence classes of integers), or the set of *p*-adic integers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The *whole numbers* were synonymous with the integers up until the early 1950s.
[src:styx-rule/integer] In the late 1950s, as part of the New Math movement, American elementary school teachers began teaching that *whole numbers* referred to the natural numbers, excluding negative numbers, while *integer* included the negative numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The *whole numbers* remain ambiguous to the present day.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Like the natural numbers, ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is closed under the operations of addition and multiplication, that is, the sum and product of any two integers is an integer.
[src:styx-rule/integer] However, with the inclusion of the negative natural numbers (and importantly, 0), ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, unlike the natural numbers, is also closed under subtraction.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The integers form a ring which is the most basic one, in the following sense: for any ring, there is a unique ring homomorphism from the integers into this ring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This universal property, namely to be an initial object in the category of rings, characterizes the ring ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This unique homomorphism is injective if and only if the characteristic of the ring is zero.
[src:styx-rule/integer] It follows that every ring of characteristic zero contains a subring isomorphic to ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, which is its smallest subring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is not closed under division, since the quotient of two integers (e.g., 1 divided by 2) need not be an integer.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Although the natural numbers are closed under exponentiation, the integers are not (since the result can be a fraction when the exponent is negative).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The first five properties listed above for addition say that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, under addition, is an abelian group.
[src:styx-rule/integer] It is also a cyclic group, since every non-zero integer can be written as a finite sum 1 + 1 + ... + 1 or (−1) + (−1) + ... + (−1).
[src:styx-rule/integer] In fact, ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ under addition is the *only* infinite cyclic group—in the sense that any infinite cyclic group is isomorphic to ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The first four properties listed above for multiplication say that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ under multiplication is a commutative monoid.
[src:styx-rule/integer] However, not every integer has a multiplicative inverse (as is the case of the number 2), which means that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ under multiplication is not a group.
[src:styx-rule/integer] All the rules from the above property table (except for the last), when taken together, say that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ together with addition and multiplication is a commutative ring with unity.
[src:styx-rule/integer] It is the prototype of all objects of such algebraic structure.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Only those equalities of expressions are true in ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ for all values of variables, which are true in any unital commutative ring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Certain non-zero integers map to zero in certain rings.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The lack of zero divisors in the integers (last property in the table) means that the commutative ring ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is an integral domain.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The lack of multiplicative inverses, which is equivalent to the fact that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is not closed under division, means that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is *not* a field.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The smallest field containing the integers as a subring is the field of rational numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The process of constructing the rationals from the integers can be mimicked to form the field of fractions of any integral domain.
[src:styx-rule/integer] And back, starting from an algebraic number field (an extension of rational numbers), its ring of integers can be extracted, which includes ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ as its subring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Although ordinary division is not defined on ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, the division "with remainder" is defined on them.
[src:styx-rule/integer] It is called Euclidean division, and possesses the following important property: given two integers *a* and *b* with *b* ≠ 0, there exist unique integers *q* and *r* such that *a* = *q* × *b* + *r* and 0 ≤ *r* < |*b*|, where |*b*| denotes the absolute value of *b*.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The integer *q* is called the *quotient* and *r* is called the *remainder* of the division of *a* by *b*.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The Euclidean algorithm for computing greatest common divisors works by a sequence of Euclidean divisions.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The above says that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is a Euclidean domain.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This implies that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is a principal ideal domain, and any positive integer can be written as the products of primes in an essentially unique way.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:styx-rule/integer] ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is a totally ordered set without upper or lower bound.
[src:styx-rule/integer] An integer is *positive* if it is greater than zero, and *negative* if it is less than zero.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Zero is defined as neither negative nor positive.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Thus it follows that ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ together with the above ordering is an ordered ring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The integers are the only nontrivial totally ordered abelian group whose positive elements are well-ordered.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This is equivalent to the statement that any Noetherian valuation ring is either a field—or a discrete valuation ring.
[src:styx-rule/integer] In elementary school teaching, integers are often intuitively defined as the union of the (positive) natural numbers, zero, and the negations of the natural numbers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] First construct the set of natural numbers according to the Peano axioms, call this ⁠ P ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Then construct a set ⁠ $P^{-}$ ⁠ which is disjoint from ⁠ P ⁠ and in one-to-one correspondence with ⁠ P ⁠ via a function ⁠ $\psi$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] For example, take ⁠ $P^{-}$ ⁠ to be the ordered pairs ⁠ $(1,n)$ ⁠ with the mapping ⁠ $\psi =n\mapsto (1,n)$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Finally let 0 be some object not in ⁠ P ⁠ or ⁠ $P^{-}$ ⁠, for example the ordered pair (0,0).
[src:styx-rule/integer] Then the integers are defined to be the union ⁠ $P\cup P^{-}\cup \{0\}$ ⁠.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The traditional arithmetic operations can then be defined on the integers in a piecewise fashion, for each of positive numbers, negative numbers, and zero.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The traditional style of definition leads to many different cases (each arithmetic operation needs to be defined on each combination of types of integer) and makes it tedious to prove that integers obey the various laws of arithmetic.
[src:styx-rule/integer] In modern set-theoretic mathematics, a more abstract construction allowing one to define arithmetical operations without any case distinction is often used instead.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The integers can thus be formally constructed as the equivalence classes of ordered pairs of natural numbers (*a*,*b*).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The intuition is that (*a*,*b*) stands for the result of subtracting *b* from *a*.
[src:styx-rule/integer] It is easily verified that these definitions are independent of the choice of representatives of the equivalence classes.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Every equivalence class has a unique member that is of the form (*n*,0) or (0,*n*) (or both at once).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The natural number *n* is identified with the class [(*n*,0)] (i.e., the natural numbers are embedded into the integers by map sending *n* to [(*n*,0)]), and the class [(0,*n*)] is denoted −*n* (this covers all remaining classes, and gives the class [(0,0)] a second time since −0 = 0.
[src:styx-rule/integer] If the natural numbers are identified with the corresponding integers (using the embedding mentioned above), this convention creates no ambiguity.
[src:styx-rule/integer] This notation recovers the familiar representation of the integers as {..., −2, −1, 0, 1, 2, ...} .
[src:styx-rule/integer] In theoretical computer science, other approaches for the construction of integers are used by automated theorem provers and term rewrite engines.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Integers are represented as algebraic terms built using a few basic operations (e.g., **zero**, **succ**, **pred**) and using natural numbers, which are assumed to be already constructed (using the Peano approach).
[src:styx-rule/integer] There exist at least ten such constructions of signed integers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] The technique for the construction of integers presented in the previous section corresponds to the particular case where there is a single basic operation **pair** $(x,y)$ that takes as arguments two natural numbers ⁠ x ⁠ and ⁠ y ⁠, and returns an integer (equal to ⁠ $x-y$ ⁠).
[src:styx-rule/integer] This operation is not free since the integer 0 can be written **pair**(0,0), or **pair**(1,1), or **pair**(2,2), etc..
[src:styx-rule/integer] This technique of construction is used by the proof assistant Isabelle; however, many other tools use alternative construction techniques, notable those based upon free constructors, which are simpler and can be implemented more efficiently in computers.
[src:styx-rule/integer] An integer is often a primitive data type in computer languages.
[src:styx-rule/integer] However, integer data types can only represent a subset of all integers, since practical computers are of finite capacity.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Also, in the common two's complement representation, the inherent definition of sign distinguishes between "negative" and "non-negative" rather than "negative, positive, and 0".
[src:styx-rule/integer] (It is, however, certainly possible for a computer to determine whether an integer value is truly positive.) Fixed length integer approximation data types (or subsets) are denoted *int* or Integer in several programming languages (such as Algol68, C, Java, Delphi, etc.).
[src:styx-rule/integer] Variable-length representations of integers, such as bignums, can store any integer that fits in the computer's memory.
[src:styx-rule/integer] Other integer data types are implemented with a fixed size, usually a number of bits which is a power of 2 (4, 8, 16, etc.) or a memorable number of decimal digits (e.g., 9 or 10).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The set of integers is countably infinite, meaning it is possible to pair each integer with a unique natural number.
[src:styx-rule/integer] More technically, the cardinality of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ is said to equal ℵ0 (aleph-null).
[src:styx-rule/integer] The pairing between elements of ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is called a bijection.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In mathematics, the **sign** of a real number is its property of being either positive, negative, or 0.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Depending on local conventions, zero may be considered as having its own unique sign, having no sign, or having both positive and negative sign.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In some contexts, it makes sense to distinguish between a positive and a negative zero.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In mathematics and physics, the phrase "change of sign" is associated with exchanging an object for its additive inverse (multiplication with −1, negation), an operation which is not restricted to real numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] It applies among other objects to vectors, matrices, and complex numbers, which are not prescribed to be only either positive, negative, or zero.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The word "sign" is also often used to indicate binary aspects of mathematical or scientific objects, such as odd and even (sign of a permutation), sense of orientation or rotation (cw/ccw), one sided limits, and other concepts described in § Other meanings below.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Numbers from various number systems, like integers, rationals, complex numbers, quaternions, octonions, ... may have multiple attributes, that fix certain properties of a number.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] A number system that bears the structure of an ordered ring contains a unique number that when added with any number leaves the latter unchanged.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This unique number is known as the system's additive identity element.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, the integers has the structure of an ordered ring.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Because of the total order in this ring, there are numbers greater than zero, called the *positive* numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Another property required for a ring to be ordered is that, for each positive number, there exists a unique corresponding number less than 0 whose sum with the original positive number is 0.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] These numbers less than 0 are called the *negative* numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The numbers in each such pair are their respective additive inverses.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This attribute of a number, being exclusively either *zero* (0), *positive* (+), or *negative* (−), is called its **sign**, and is often encoded to the real numbers 0, 1, and −1, respectively (similar to the way the sign function is defined).
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Since rational and real numbers are also ordered rings (in fact ordered fields), the *sign* attribute also applies to these number systems.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] When a minus sign is used in between two numbers, it represents the binary operation of subtraction.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] When a minus sign is written before a single number, it represents the unary operation of yielding the additive inverse (sometimes called *negation*) of the operand.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Abstractly then, the difference of two number is the sum of the minuend with the additive inverse of the subtrahend.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] While 0 is its own additive inverse (−0 = 0), the additive inverse of a positive number is negative, and the additive inverse of a negative number is positive.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] A double application of this operation is written as −(−3) = 3.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The plus sign is predominantly used in algebra to denote the binary operation of addition, and only rarely to emphasize the positivity of an expression.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In common numeral notation (used in arithmetic and elsewhere), the sign of a number is often made explicit by placing a plus or a minus sign before the number.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, +3 denotes "positive three", and −3 denotes "negative three" (algebraically: the additive inverse of 3).
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Without specific context (or when no explicit sign is given), a number is interpreted per default as positive.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This notation establishes a strong association of the minus sign "−" with negative numbers, and the plus sign "+" with positive numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Within the convention of zero being neither positive nor negative, a specific sign-value 0 may be assigned to the number value 0.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This is exploited in the $\operatorname {sgn}$ -function, as defined for real numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In arithmetic, +0 and −0 both denote the same number 0.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] There is generally no danger of confusing the value with its sign, although the convention of assigning both signs to 0 does not immediately allow for this discrimination.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In certain European countries, e.g. in Belgium and France, 0 is considered to be *both* positive and negative following the convention set forth by Nicolas Bourbaki.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In some contexts, such as floating-point representations of real numbers within computers, it is useful to consider signed versions of zero, with signed zeros referring to different, discrete number representations (see signed number representations for more).
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The symbols +0 and −0 rarely appear as substitutes for 0+ and 0−, used in calculus and mathematical analysis for one-sided limits (right-sided limit and left-sided limit, respectively).
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This notation refers to the behaviour of a function as its real input variable approaches 0 along positive (resp., negative) values; the two limits need not exist or agree.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, the absolute value of a real number is always "non-negative", but is not necessarily "positive" in the first interpretation, whereas in the second interpretation, it is called "positive"—though not necessarily "strictly positive".
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The same terminology is sometimes used for functions that yield real or other signed values.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, a function would be called a *positive function* if its values are positive for all arguments of its domain, or a *non-negative function* if all of its values are non-negative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Complex numbers are impossible to order, so they cannot carry the structure of an ordered ring, and, accordingly, cannot be partitioned into positive and negative complex numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] They do, however, share an attribute with the reals, which is called *absolute value* or *magnitude*.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Magnitudes are always non-negative real numbers, and to any non-zero number there belongs a positive real number, its absolute value.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, the absolute value of −3 and the absolute value of 3 are both equal to 3.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This is written in symbols as |−3| = 3 and |3| = 3.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In general, any arbitrary real value can be specified by its magnitude and its sign.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Using the standard encoding, any real value is given by the product of the magnitude and the sign in standard encoding.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This relation can be generalized to define a *sign* for complex numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Since the real and complex numbers both form a field and contain the positive reals, they also contain the reciprocals of the magnitudes of all non-zero numbers.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This means that any non-zero number may be multiplied with the reciprocal of its magnitude, that is, divided by its magnitude.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] It is immediate that the quotient of any non-zero real number by its magnitude yields exactly its sign.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] By analogy, the **sign of a complex number** z can be defined as the quotient of z and its magnitude |*z*|.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The sign of a complex number is the exponential of the product of its argument with the imaginary unit. represents in some sense its complex argument.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This is to be compared to the sign of real numbers, except with $e^{i\pi }=-1.$ For the definition of a complex sign-function. see § Complex sign function below.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] When dealing with numbers, it is often convenient to have their sign available as a number.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This is accomplished by functions that extract the sign of any number, and map it to a predefined value before making it available for further calculations.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For example, it might be advantageous to formulate an intricate algorithm for positive values only, and take care of the sign only afterwards.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] For non-zero values of x, this function can also be defined by the formula $\operatorname {sgn}(x)={\frac {x}{|x|}}={\frac {|x|}{x}},$ where |*x*| is the absolute value of x.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] While a real number has a 1-dimensional direction, a complex number has a 2-dimensional direction.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] This definition may also be recognized as a normalized vector, that is, a vector whose direction is unchanged, and whose length is fixed to unity.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] If the original value was R,θ in polar form, then sign(R, θ) is 1 θ.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Extension of sign() or signum() to any number of dimensions is obvious, but this has already been defined as normalizing a vector.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In situations where there are exactly two possibilities on equal footing for an attribute, these are often labelled by convention as *plus* and *minus*, respectively.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In some contexts, the choice of this assignment (i.e., which range of values is considered positive and which negative) is natural, whereas in other contexts, the choice is arbitrary, making an explicit sign convention necessary, the only requirement being consistent use of the convention.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In many contexts, it is common to associate a sign with the measure of an angle, particularly an oriented angle or an angle of rotation.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In such a situation, the sign indicates whether the angle is in the clockwise or counterclockwise direction.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Though different conventions can be used, it is common in mathematics to have counterclockwise angles count as positive, and clockwise angles count as negative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] It is also possible to associate a sign to an angle of rotation in three dimensions, assuming that the axis of rotation has been oriented.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Specifically, a right-handed rotation around an oriented axis typically counts as positive, while a left-handed rotation counts as negative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] An angle which is the negative of a given angle has an equal arc, but the opposite axis.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Using this convention, an increase in *x* counts as positive change, while a decrease of *x* counts as negative change.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In calculus, this same convention is used in the definition of the derivative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] As a result, any increasing function has positive derivative, while any decreasing function has negative derivative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] When studying one-dimensional displacements and motions in analytic geometry and physics, it is common to label the two possible directions as positive and negative.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Because the number line is usually drawn with positive numbers to the right, and negative numbers to the left, a common convention is for motions to the right to be given a positive sign, and for motions to the left to be given a negative sign.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] On the Cartesian plane, the rightward and upward directions are usually thought of as positive, with rightward being the positive *x*-direction, and upward being the positive *y*-direction.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] If a displacement vector is separated into its vector components, then the horizontal part will be positive for motion to the right and negative for motion to the left, while the vertical part will be positive for motion upward and negative for motion downward.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Likewise, a negative speed (rate of change of displacement) implies a velocity in the opposite direction, i.e., receding instead of advancing; a special case is the radial speed.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In 3D space, notions related to sign can be found in the two normal orientations and orientability in general.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In computing, an integer value may be either signed or unsigned, depending on whether the computer is keeping track of a sign for the number.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] By restricting an integer variable to non-negative values only, one more bit can be used for storing the value of a number.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Because of the way integer arithmetic is done within computers, signed number representations usually do not store the sign as a single independent bit, instead using e.g. two's complement.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] In contrast, real numbers are stored and manipulated as floating point values.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] The floating point values are represented using three separate values, mantissa, exponent, and sign.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Given this separate sign bit, it is possible to represent both positive and negative zero.
[src:styx-rule/non-negative] Most programming languages normally treat positive zero and negative zero as equivalent values, albeit, they provide means by which the distinction can be detected.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] In chemistry the **polyhedral skeletal electron pair theory** (PSEPT) provides electron counting rules useful for predicting the structures of clusters such as borane and carborane clusters.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The electron counting rules were originally formulated by Kenneth Wade, and were further developed by others including Michael Mingos; they are sometimes known as **Wade's rules** or the **Wade–Mingos rules**.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The rules are based on a molecular orbital treatment of the bonding.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] These rules have been extended and unified in the form of the Jemmis *mno* rules.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Different rules (4*n*, 5*n*, or 6*n*) are invoked depending on the number of electrons per vertex.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The 4*n* rules are reasonably accurate in predicting the structures of clusters having about 4 electrons per vertex, as is the case for many boranes and carboranes.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] For such clusters, the structures are based on deltahedra, which are polyhedra in which every face is triangular.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The 4*n* clusters are classified as *closo-*, *nido-*, *arachno-* or *hypho-*, based on whether they represent a complete (*closo-*) deltahedron, or a deltahedron that is missing one (*nido-*), two (*arachno-*) or three (*hypho-*) vertices.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] However, hypho clusters are relatively uncommon due to the fact that the electron count is high enough to start to fill antibonding orbitals and destabilize the 4*n* structure.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] If the electron count is close to 5 electrons per vertex, the structure often changes to one governed by the 5n rules, which are based on 3-connected polyhedra.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] As the electron count increases further, the structures of clusters with 5n electron counts become unstable, so the 6*n* rules can be implemented.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The 6*n* clusters have structures that are based on rings.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] A molecular orbital treatment can be used to rationalize the bonding of cluster compounds of the 4*n*, 5*n*, and 6*n* types.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The following polyhedra are *closo* polyhedra, and are the basis for the 4*n* rules; each of these have triangular faces.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The number of vertices in the cluster determines what polyhedron the structure is based on.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Using the electron count, the predicted structure can be found.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] *n* is the number of vertices in the cluster.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The 4*n* rules are enumerated in the following table.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] When counting electrons for each cluster, the number of valence electrons is enumerated.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] For each transition metal present, 10 electrons are subtracted from the total electron count.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] For example, in Rh6(CO)16 the total number of electrons would be 6 × 9 + 16 × 2 − 6 × 10 = 86 – 60 = 26.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Therefore, the cluster is a *closo* polyhedron because *n* = 6, with 4*n* + 2 = 26.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Larger and more electropositive atoms tend to occupy vertices of high connectivity and smaller more electronegative atoms tend to occupy vertices of low connectivity.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] In the special case of boron hydride clusters, each boron atom connected to 3 or more vertices has one terminal hydride, while a boron atom connected to two other vertices has two terminal hydrogen atoms.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] If more hydrogen atoms are present, they are placed in open face positions to even out the coordination number of the vertices.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] For the special case of transition metal clusters, ligands are added to the metal centers to give the metals reasonable coordination numbers, and if any hydrogen atoms are present they are placed in bridging positions to even out the coordination numbers of the vertices.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] In general, *closo* structures with *n* vertices are *n*-vertex polyhedra.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] To predict the structure of a *nido* cluster, the *closo* cluster with *n* + 1 vertices is used as a starting point; if the cluster is composed of small atoms a high connectivity vertex is removed, while if the cluster is composed of large atoms a low connectivity vertex is removed.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Electron count: 10 × Pb + 2 (for the negative charge) = 10 × 4 + 2 = 42 electrons.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Electron count: 4 × S – 2 (for the positive charge) = 4 × 6 – 2 = 22 electrons.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Starting from an octahedron, a vertex of high connectivity is removed, and then a non-adjacent vertex is removed.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Starting from a trigonal bipyramid, a face is capped.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The carbonyls have been omitted for clarity.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Starting from an octahedron, one of the vertices is removed.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The rules are useful in also predicting the structure of carboranes.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The bookkeeping for deltahedral clusters is sometimes carried out by counting skeletal electrons instead of the total number of electrons.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] As discussed previously, the 4*n* rule mainly deals with clusters with electron counts of 4*n* + *k*, in which approximately 4 electrons are on each vertex.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] As more electrons are added per vertex, the number of the electrons per vertex approaches 5.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Rather than adopting structures based on deltahedra, the 5n-type clusters have structures based on a different series of polyhedra known as the 3-connected polyhedra, in which each vertex is connected to 3 other vertices.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The 3-connected polyhedra are the duals of the deltahedra.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The common types of 3-connected polyhedra are listed below.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] As more electrons are added to a 5*n* cluster, the number of electrons per vertex approaches 6.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Instead of adopting structures based on 4*n* or 5*n* rules, the clusters tend to have structures governed by the 6*n* rules, which are based on rings.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The rules for the 6*n* structures are as follows.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Electron count = 8 × S = 8 × 6 = 48 electrons.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] = 48, so the cluster is an 8-membered ring.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] + 2 = 38, so the cluster is a 6-membered chain.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Provided a vertex unit is isolobal with BH then it can, in principle at least, be substituted for a BH unit, even though BH and CH are not isoelectronic.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The CH+ unit is isolobal, hence the rules are applicable to carboranes.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] This can be explained due to a frontier orbital treatment.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Additionally there are isolobal transition-metal units.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] For example, Fe(CO)3 provides 2 electrons.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The boron atoms lie on each vertex of the octahedron and are sp hybridized.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] One sp-hybrid radiates away from the structure forming the bond with the hydrogen atom.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The other sp-hybrid radiates into the center of the structure forming a large bonding molecular orbital at the center of the cluster.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The remaining two unhybridized orbitals lie along the tangent of the sphere like structure creating more bonding and antibonding orbitals between the boron vertices.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] The total skeletal bonding orbitals is therefore 7, i.e.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Transition metal clusters use the d orbitals for bonding.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Thus, they have up to nine bonding orbitals, instead of only the four present in boron and main group clusters.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] Owing their large radii, transition metals generally form clusters that are larger than main group elements.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] One consequence of their increased size, these clusters often contain atoms at their centers.
[src:styx-rule/polyhedral-skeletal-electron-pair-theory] In such cases, the rules of electron counting assume that the interstitial atom contributes all valence electrons to cluster bonding.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] The **styx rule**, also known as **Lipscomb's styx rule**, can be used to calculate the structures of boranes.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] It was developed by William Lipscomb in 1954.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] The bonding structure deduced by the styx rule doesn't reflect the true symmetry of boranes.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] More modern methods that more accurately reflect the bonding nature of boranes like Wade's rules have been developed.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] When given the chemical formula of a borane (BmHn), one can deduce its styx numbers by first separating the formula into (BH)mHn-m.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] With these, one can come up with several integer combinations of styx.
[src:styx-rule/styx-rule] However, some are ruled out because styx are non-negative.
